SIMPLE: operation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Operation
<hw>Op`er*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>operatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>op⟦eacute⟧ration</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or process of operating; agency; the exertion
of power, physical, mechanical, or moral.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The pain and sickness caused by manna are the effects of its
<qex>operation</qex> on the stomach.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Speculative painting, without the assistance of manual
<qex>operation</qex>, can never attain to perfection.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The method of working; mode of action.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is operated or accomplished; an effect
brought about in accordance with a definite plan; <as>as, military or
naval <ex>operations</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Effect produced; influence.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The bards . . . had great <qex>operation</qex> on the vulgar.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>Something to be done; some
transformation to be made upon quantities or mathematical objects, the
transformation being indicated either by rules or symbols.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>Any methodical action of the
hand, or of the hand with instruments, on the human body, to produce a
curative or remedial effect, as in amputation, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Calculus of operations</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Calculus</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>operational</ent>⟦br⟧
